<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,1465,2032]" box="[199,1105,1609,1636]" pageId="14" pageNumber="291">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1609,1635]" pageId="14" pageNumber="291">Description.</emphasis>
Male (
<figureCitation box="[424,532,1610,1636]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="13.[151,250,2011,2035]" captionTargetBox="[175,1410,534,1979]" captionTargetId="figure-154@13.[164,1422,525,1988]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 12. Habitus of Hexarhopalus (L.) qiului sp. nov. A. Male; B. Female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4440950" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4440950/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="291">Figs 12A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[543,629,1610,1636]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1179,1203]" captionTargetBox="[156,1431,186,1150]" captionTargetId="figure-26@14.[151,1436,181,1155]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 13. Diagnostic features of Hexarhopalus (L.) qiului sp. nov. (A–G. Male; H–I. Female). A. Head and pronotum, in dorsal view; B. Antenna; C. Aedeagus, ventral view; D. Same, lateral view; E. Same, dorsal view; F. Spiculum gastrale; G. Abdominal ventrite VIII of male; H. Ventrite VIII of female and spiculum; I. Ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4440952" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4440952/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="291">
13A 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[591,605,1610,1636]" pageId="14" pageNumber="291">–</emphasis>
G
</figureCitation>
). Body elongate, black, convex and crude.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,1465,2032]" pageId="14" pageNumber="291">
Head (
<figureCitation box="[274,376,1646,1672]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1179,1203]" captionTargetBox="[156,1431,186,1150]" captionTargetId="figure-26@14.[151,1436,181,1155]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 13. Diagnostic features of Hexarhopalus (L.) qiului sp. nov. (A–G. Male; H–I. Female). A. Head and pronotum, in dorsal view; B. Antenna; C. Aedeagus, ventral view; D. Same, lateral view; E. Same, dorsal view; F. Spiculum gastrale; G. Abdominal ventrite VIII of male; H. Ventrite VIII of female and spiculum; I. Ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4440952" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4440952/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="291">Fig. 13A</figureCitation>
) distinctly transverse, dorsal surface covered with dense big punctures and short hairs, length of hairs equal to about 1.5 times of diameters of the eye facets. Labrum narrower than clypeus, covered with bristles of medium length in apical portion. Antennal tubercles weak, antenna (
<figureCitation box="[945,1045,1718,1744]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1179,1203]" captionTargetBox="[156,1431,186,1150]" captionTargetId="figure-26@14.[151,1436,181,1155]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 13. Diagnostic features of Hexarhopalus (L.) qiului sp. nov. (A–G. Male; H–I. Female). A. Head and pronotum, in dorsal view; B. Antenna; C. Aedeagus, ventral view; D. Same, lateral view; E. Same, dorsal view; F. Spiculum gastrale; G. Abdominal ventrite VIII of male; H. Ventrite VIII of female and spiculum; I. Ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4440952" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4440952/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="291">Fig. 13B</figureCitation>
) slightly longer than the combined length of head and pronotum, clubs loosely formed by apical four antennomeres. Antennomere I slightly expanded; II shortest, longer than wide; III longest, about 2.5 times as long as II, IV-VI similar, shorter than III, VII expanded at apex; apical four dark brown, expanded, XI with rounded apex.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,1465,2032]" pageId="14" pageNumber="291">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[326,428,1862,1888]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1179,1203]" captionTargetBox="[156,1431,186,1150]" captionTargetId="figure-26@14.[151,1436,181,1155]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 13. Diagnostic features of Hexarhopalus (L.) qiului sp. nov. (A–G. Male; H–I. Female). A. Head and pronotum, in dorsal view; B. Antenna; C. Aedeagus, ventral view; D. Same, lateral view; E. Same, dorsal view; F. Spiculum gastrale; G. Abdominal ventrite VIII of male; H. Ventrite VIII of female and spiculum; I. Ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4440952" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4440952/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="291">Fig. 13A</figureCitation>
) strongly concave at middle, and about as long as wide, widest at middle, dorsal surface covered with dense big punctures and short hairs, punctures of pronotum are formed to strong wrinkles. Groove of pronotum much deep at base, the back angle oblique indentation slightly short, deep, curved forward and upward. Lateral groove continuously connected with the back angle oblique indentation, deep and much wider, other two groove on pronotum shallow and not obvious, median line not obvious.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,151,1005]" pageId="15" pageNumber="292">Elytra about twice as long as wide, widest at apical 1/3, shoulders strong, Disc with regular rows of orderly foveolate punctres, scutellum transverse, near triangular. Hind wings fully developed.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,151,1005]" pageId="15" pageNumber="292">Femora strongly expanded at middle, all tibiae covered with brown setae at apex, protibiae and mesotibiae obviously curved. All legs dark brown at basal part, and with black apex.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,151,1005]" pageId="15" pageNumber="292">
Aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[325,409,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1179,1203]" captionTargetBox="[156,1431,186,1150]" captionTargetId="figure-26@14.[151,1436,181,1155]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 13. Diagnostic features of Hexarhopalus (L.) qiului sp. nov. (A–G. Male; H–I. Female). A. Head and pronotum, in dorsal view; B. Antenna; C. Aedeagus, ventral view; D. Same, lateral view; E. Same, dorsal view; F. Spiculum gastrale; G. Abdominal ventrite VIII of male; H. Ventrite VIII of female and spiculum; I. Ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4440952" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4440952/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="292">Figs 13</figureCitation>
C–E), near symmetrical, abdominal ventrite VIII (
<figureCitation box="[977,1079,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1179,1203]" captionTargetBox="[156,1431,186,1150]" captionTargetId="figure-26@14.[151,1436,181,1155]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 13. Diagnostic features of Hexarhopalus (L.) qiului sp. nov. (A–G. Male; H–I. Female). A. Head and pronotum, in dorsal view; B. Antenna; C. Aedeagus, ventral view; D. Same, lateral view; E. Same, dorsal view; F. Spiculum gastrale; G. Abdominal ventrite VIII of male; H. Ventrite VIII of female and spiculum; I. Ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4440952" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4440952/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="292">Fig. 13G</figureCitation>
) deeply split medially at posterior margin and with long hairs at hind margin. Spiculum gastrale (
<figureCitation box="[889,985,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1179,1203]" captionTargetBox="[156,1431,186,1150]" captionTargetId="figure-26@14.[151,1436,181,1155]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 13. Diagnostic features of Hexarhopalus (L.) qiului sp. nov. (A–G. Male; H–I. Female). A. Head and pronotum, in dorsal view; B. Antenna; C. Aedeagus, ventral view; D. Same, lateral view; E. Same, dorsal view; F. Spiculum gastrale; G. Abdominal ventrite VIII of male; H. Ventrite VIII of female and spiculum; I. Ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4440952" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4440952/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="292">Fig. 13F</figureCitation>
) dissymmetrical, short, with large apical lobes and apex with varying lengths hairs.
</paragraph>
